<% if session[:tutorial] == :on %>
  <div class="hf left" id='hf-types'>
    <div class="num">1</div>
    <div class="c">
      <div>Types</div>
      <ul>
        <li class='b'>Topics can have types, which are also topics.</li>
        <li>Topic types help Limelight organize topics and feeds.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="hf left" id='hf-popularity'>
    <div class="num">2</div>
    <div class="c">
      <div>Popularity</div>
      <ul>
        <li>We need to fill this tutorial in!</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="hf left" id="hf-follow">
    <div class="num">3</div>
    <div class="c">
      <div>Follow</div>
      <ul>
        <li>When you follow a topic, posts mentioning the topic will be added to your feed.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="hf left" id="hf-aliases">
    <div class="num">4</div>
    <div class="c">
      <div>Aliases</div>
      <ul>
        <li class="b">Topics often have a few names.</li>
        <li>Aliases allow users to mention topics in different ways.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="hf left" id="hf-connections">
    <div class="num">5</div>
    <div class="c">
      <div>Connections</div>
      <ul>
        <li class="b">Connections create a web of related topics on Limelight.</li>
        <li>
          Limelight uses connections to intelligently pull relevant posts into topic feeds.
          For example, the Apple topic will show posts mentioning Apple as well as posts mentioning Apple
          products, like the iPhone.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
<% end %>